container-title: End of the ‘Dark Ages’, beginning of the Middle Ages?
title: The expansion of Islam. For some this marks the beginning of the Middle Ages. 719–41 Carolingian Renaissance: The first of many renaissances

note: 980–1037 Avicenna: One of the major Arabic commentators on Aristotle, and big influence on Aquinas.
title: Coronation of Charlemagne: First emperor of the Holy Roman Empire. The boundaries of the Holy Roman Empire are the boundaries of the political-social-historical Middle Ages for some
St Anselm (he of the ontological argument
The Church starts to become independent of secular authorities and the Holy Roman emperor. First signs of the split between Church and State – essential to modern Western political thought
Peter Abelard (logician and theologian, ill-fated lover of Heloise
The First Crusade begins. The Second (1146–8); the Third (1188–92); the Fourth (1202–4); the Fifth
Some smaller Crusades continued in the East into the sixteenth century
Averroes: A major Arabic commentator on Aristotle. Poster boy of the so-called ‘Latin Averroists’, Siger of Brabant and Boethius of Dacia of the late thirteenth century
Maimonides (he of Guide to the Perplexed
A heretical group called the Cathars in the south of France is crushed. The struggle with heresy, around since the beginning of the organized Church, continues

note: 1225–74 Thomas Aquinas and the ‘Golden Age’ of Scholasticism in full bloom.
title: Until now only some logical works of the Organon had been known. Now the metaphysics, ethics, politics and scientific works are read
John Duns Scotus: Scotland’s most influential scholastic thinker
William of Ockham (he of ‘the razor’): England’s most influential scholastic thinker, who died of plague
Petrarch becomes poet laureate. For some this marks the end of the Middle Ages
The Great Schism. A Pope in Rome and another in Avignon! Incalculable damage done to the prestige of the Church
Leonardo da Vince: The renaissance in full bloom
Constantinople taken by the Ottomans. Scholars fleeing Ottoman rule head west, and contribute to the Renaissance. This marks the end of the Middle Ages for some
War of the Roses: English civil war, fighting over which royal family will rule
1468–1534 Cardinal Cajetan, begins the post-nominalist revival of Aquinas
Copernicus: This polish man of the Church revolutionizes astronomy
Columbus sets out for America. For some this marks the end of the Middle Ages

container-title: Publication of Erasmus’s In Praise of Folly

title: Palestrina (Giovanni Pierluigi da) Renaissance composer of scared music. Pinnacle of polyphony
Siege of Vienna by the Ottomans

Defends Copernicus in his Dialogue Concerning the Two Chief World Systems. Clashes with the Catholic Church over his realism regarding astronomical systems (the Church was anti-realist vis-à-vis astronomy). 1564–1616 Shakespeare
Thomas Hobbes: Founder of English moral and political philosophy
Rene Descartes: Poster boy of the Early Modern period
British empiricism begins
Cartesian rationalism continues
A new physics with lasting impact
Leibniz: Last canonical figure to be fully versed in scholastic thought (particularly Suarez)?
Johan Sebastien Bach: Pinnacle of Baroque music

container-title: End of the Middle Ages in England?
title: The Glorious Revolution: England’s much less bloody version of the French Revolution. A king who must respect a House of Parliament with elected representatives is established
Hume and Newton reconciled by the ‘Copernican Turn’
This year marks the publication of Richard Cantillon’s An Essay on Economic Theory, written in 1730s, styled the ‘cradle of political economy’
Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart: Principal figure of the golden age of classical music
Ludwig van Beethoven: Pinnacle of classical music

American ‘Revolutionary’ Wars – a war of independence rather than a revolution. ‘No taxation without representation!’ The Federalist Papers and the American Constitution itself show how a people can rule itself without a king
Publication of Adam Smith’s The Wealth of Nations
The first major Continental power to get rid of the monarchy (in any form). For some this marks the end of the Middle Ages

Napoleonic wars. The great trauma of the early nineteenth century. Castlereagh (British foreign minister) and Metternich (Austrian foreign minister) put Europe back together again. But tension gradually increases between the new revolutionary powers (Britain and France) and the old world monarchies of Austria, Prussia and Russia
1806 Dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire by Napoleon (end of the political-social-historical Middle Ages by my lights
Revolutions in Western and Central Europe continue the democratic and anti-monarchist thrust of the French Revolution
The Reform Act in UK. The vote now extended to non-property owners

publisher: Publication of Karl Marx’s Das Capital

title: Germany unified under Bismarck
First Austrian and German houses fall/Russian Revolution. The World War end of (effective) monarchy in Europe. Perhaps this is the end of the Middle Ages?
